Lots of errors here! Lets look at the columns and see if we can convert them into factors (or Boolean) for analysis.

colnames(df)[c(2,4,5,6,7)]
## [1] "Day"      "Deaths"   "Injuries" "Mw"       "Depth"

I dont think I can do anything with Day Mw or Depth but I could ask if there were any Deaths or Injuries since most were zeroed out in my data.

df <- df %>% mutate(
  Deaths = (Deaths > 0),
  Injuries = (Injuries >0)
)

Then Ill run the transactions again and see how it has cleaned up.

as(df,"transactions")
## Warning: Column(s) 2, 6, 7 not logical or factor. Applying default
## discretization (see '? discretizeDF').

trans <- transactions(df)
## Warning: Column(s) 2, 6, 7 not logical or factor. Applying default
## discretization (see '? discretizeDF').

I am happy to let R do the default discretization of the rest of the data. Partly because what is left I could not come up with better cutoffs. Depth, Mw and Day nothing strikes me as important. Day might be important in stock data but for a natural phenomenon, I can see no reason to chop it differently.

Now well build some rules. Very similar to looking at frequent!
